You&#39;re right, whne it comes down to it, it&#39;s all about the $$.  I  used to pick up injured and sick animals and only occasionally would a  caring vet work with me by discounting or payments.  Do you have a  vet school nearby?  Maybe you could call around to see if another  one will work with you on the dog.  Also, call the dog or cat  rescue in your area and ask them what can be done.  Like I said  before, I will contribute.  If the whole group gave a few $$, you  could tell the vet donations will be forthcoming.  If you can get  the leg set, it might be slow healing.  I had a cat that had a  fracture femur and I carried the poor thing to the litter pan at  regular intervals, and the leg healed.  It can be done.  Even  if it is amputated, the dog could make it on three (not as easy with an  elderly dog).  

  Joanne 

Frank Sumption &lt;franks-boxes@...&gt; wrote:                                             It  wasn&#39;t taken like that. The only thing that really chaps my hide  is these god damn medical people, they profess how much they care--yeah  care your friggin&#39; wallet! We can&#39;t get any of them to extend  payments over the next couple month to get the dog&#39;s leg set, it  all has to be up front! This society is so brainwashed, and dead set on  money I think it has turned completey evil. For $800 bucks they  can amputate, f----- evil nasty bastards. You should have heard that  tired ass vet himhaw around why they couldn&#39;t just set the damn bones!  It&#39;s a clean, straight across break! Even my wife was appalled at  how blatent it is that it&#39;s all about the money, and how much they can  squeeze out of a person. 

   Frank-S




